1. What are Security Models?
Security models are frameworks used to enforce and evaluate security policies in systems.
They:

Define how data is accessed and protected
Help ensure the CIA triad:

Confidentiality – prevent unauthorised access
Integrity – ensure data accuracy
Availability – ensure data is accessible when needed

2. The CIA Triad (Core Concept)
🔒 Confidentiality
Data only accessible to authorised users
Protection methods:

Encryption
Authentication
Access control

Threats:
Eavesdropping
Man-in-the-middle attacks

✅ Integrity
Ensures data is accurate and not altered
Only authorised users can modify data
Protection methods:

Hashing
Validation controls

Threats:
Human error
System failures

⚡ Availability
Systems/data must be accessible at all times
Maintained through:

Backups
System maintenance
Failover systems

Threats:
DDoS attacks
Hardware failure

3. Main Security Models
🔐 1. Bell-LaPadula Model (Confidentiality-focused)
Prevents unauthorised access to sensitive data
Used in military/government systems

Rules:
No Read Up → you can’t read higher-level data
No Write Down → you can’t write to lower-level data
Strong Rule → only same-level read/write

👉 Focus: Protect secrecy
✅ 2. Biba Model (Integrity-focused)
Ensures data remains accurate and trustworthy

Rules:
No Read Down → avoid low-quality data
No Write Up → prevent corrupting higher-level data
Strong Rule → same-level only

👉 Focus: Protect data integrity
🔄 3. Clark-Wilson Model (Business/Practical Security)

Ensures data integrity through controlled processes
Used in financial and commercial systems
Key Ideas:

Users don’t access sensitive data directly
Access happens through:
Transformation processes
Verification procedures

👉 Focus: Controlled access + auditing

